  12: // including harm, and report a 2D FRONTIER (no headline multiplier).
  13: //
  14: //   Central   perceives each interested cell as V + Normal(0,noise), then attenuates
  15: //             perceived harm by gamma in [0,1]  (0 = blind to harm; 1 = full harm
  16: //             perception = a competent, accountable planner with EIA/audit/hearings).
  17: //   Distributed  a participation-p sample of the interested reveal their TRUE value
  18: //             (the funder knows their own value — no revelation noise), BUT the
  19: //             diffusely-HARMED under-participate: a citizen with v<0 participates at
  20: //             p*(1-beta). beta in [0,1] = participation bias / voice inequality
  21: //             (0 = representative turnout; 1 = the harmed are absent, Olson/bystander
  22: //             applied symmetrically). This is the SAME collective-action logic the
  23: //             model uses to justify the central's blindness, now applied to the
  24: //             platform too. The equal-wallet + default layer + low-cost objection
  25: //             channel are the design features meant to keep beta LOW.
### scripts/simulation/e4-v5-capture.mjs
   1: #!/usr/bin/env node
   2: // E4-v5 — SYMMETRIC CAPTURE game on top of the E4-v4 frictions frontier.
   3: // The adversarial review demanded capture on the distributed side; fairness demands
   4: // modelling capture on the CENTRAL too (deliberately left out of E4-v3/v4). An
   5: // organized group targets LOW-social-value projects it wants funded for private
   6: // rents. It captures a project only if profitable, a la Becker (1968):
   7: //     rent(j) > acquisition_cost + P(detection) * penalty
   8: // The asymmetry is DERIVED from the mechanism and anchored to literature, NOT chosen:
   9: //   acquisition:  CENTRAL = small FIXED cost (bribe few deciders; veto-player access,
  10: //                 Stokes 2005 needs no mass monitoring). DISTRIBUTED = scales with the
  11: //                 project (must swing many equal-wallet supporters; money can't buy
  12: //                 wallets, only persuasion).
  13: //   P(detection): CENTRAL = low & fixed (concentrated enforcement catches little -
  14: //                 Dyck-Morse-Zingales 2010: SEC 6%, auditors 14%; and citizen denuncia
  15: //                 is costly -> under-provided, Olson/Latane). DISTRIBUTED = SATURATING
  16: //                 ~1 (viral, "takes a village"; low-cost denuncia + the defrauded
  17: //                 direct-beneficiary has a monetary stake to report - the incentive
  18: //                 Dyck et al find effective).
  19: //   penalty f:    MODELLED EQUAL on both sides (conservative). Core v0's permanent
  20: //                 reputational persistence (EMA decay) is a real but UNCLAIMED margin.
  21: // The deterrence asymmetry therefore comes ONLY from p (Becker: same f, different p)
  22: // and from acquisition scaling. Ties E4 (allocation) to the +43% integrity layer.
